    "type": "SensitivityAnalysis",
    "name": "Monte Carlo sensitivity analysis — COU2 hemolysis prediction",
    "description": "A 10,000-sample Monte Carlo sensitivity analysis was performed varying eight uncertain input parameters: blood viscosity (±15%), power-law hemolysis coefficients α and β (±20% each based on published scatter in Giersiepen–Wurzinger fits), impeller tip clearance (±0.05 mm), inlet velocity profile (uniform vs. parabolic), turbulence intensity at inlet (2–8%), mesh density scaling factor (±10%), and blood density (±2%). Sobol first-order and total-order indices were computed; the dominant contributors to hemolysis index variance were the power-law coefficient α (S_T = 0.41) and tip clearance (S_T = 0.29), together accounting for 70% of total output variance. The 95th-percentile hemolysis index across all samples remained 18% below the clinical threshold, providing adequate margin even under combined worst-case uncertainty.",
    "method": "Monte Carlo with Sobol sensitivity indices",
    "dominantFactors": [
      "Power-law coefficient alpha (S_T=0.41)",
      "Impeller tip clearance (S_T=0.29)",
      "Power-law coefficient beta (S_T=0.14)"
    ],
    "sampleSize": 10000
  },
